            "old_string": "Measured on a MacBook Pro M4 Max, single RabbitMQ node via Docker, Rust 1.91. Results will vary by hardware and broker configuration. Reproducible via `cargo run -q --example stress --features rabbitmq`.\n\nThroughput is controlled by two knobs: **prefetch count** (how many messages each worker processes concurrently) and **worker count** (how many consumers in the group). The broker ceiling on a single RabbitMQ node is ~40k msg/s.\n\n### Prefetch count (concurrency per worker)\n\nHigher prefetch means more in-flight messages per worker. This is the single biggest throughput lever for I/O-bound handlers:\n\n| Handler          | prefetch=1    | prefetch=20   | Speedup  |\n|------------------|---------------|---------------|----------|\n| Fast (1-5ms)     | 222 msg/s     | 10,616 msg/s  | **48x**  |\n| Slow (50-300ms)  | 6 msg/s       | 331 msg/s     | **55x**  |\n| Heavy (1-5s)     | 0.3 msg/s     | 4 msg/s       | **13x**  |\n\nA single worker with prefetch=20 and a slow handler (331 msg/s) outperforms **64 workers** with prefetch=1 (323 msg/s).\n\n### Worker scaling\n\nAdding workers scales linearly when the handler is the bottleneck. Combine with higher prefetch for maximum throughput:\n\n| Handler          | 1 worker  | 8 workers   | 32 workers   | 64 workers   | 128 workers   |\n|------------------|-----------|-------------|--------------|--------------|---------------|\n| Fast (1-5ms)     | 222 msg/s | 1,885 msg/s | 7,543 msg/s  | 14,663 msg/s | 28,706 msg/s  |\n| Slow (50-300ms)  | 6 msg/s   | 45 msg/s    | 177 msg/s    | 323 msg/s    | 679 msg/s     |\n| Heavy (1-5s)     | 0.3 msg/s | 2 msg/s     | 7 msg/s      | 14 msg/s     | 28 msg/s      |\n\n8 workers with prefetch=20 on fast handlers hit the broker ceiling (40k msg/s). Memory stays under 10 MB even at 256 workers.",
